You can see it in the way that
they move to music. You

33:01.213 --> 33:04.382
can see it in the way
they follow rhythms.

33:04.382 --> 33:09.588
MAN: One, two, three, four.

33:09.588 --> 33:16.494
JARED BOWEN: Mary Jaffee is the
executive director of Project
STEP, a Boston organization

33:16.494 --> 33:21.600
that teases talent out of kids
who might otherwise find it
squandered. Her mission is
simple:

33:21.600 --> 33:25.237
to change the face
of classical music.

33:25.237 --> 33:32.277
MARY JAFFEE: There are so few --
in fact, virtually -- almost no
African-American and

33:32.277 --> 33:36.548
Latino musicians in
orchestras and in audiences.

33:36.548 --> 33:42.654
JARED BOWEN: Since 1982, Project
STEP has pushed to correct that
imbalance. Each year,

33:42.654 --> 33:48.360
it fans out across Boston
kindergarten classes,
identifying students with
unusual potential.

33:48.360 --> 33:52.464
MARY JAFFEE: From that 50 to 100
kids, we take in three to four a
year, so it's a very

33:52.464 --> 33:57.469
narrow bottleneck. Those
kids are highly talented.

33:57.469 --> 34:01.339
MAN: So, the trick is to play
them all in the right time.

34:01.339 --> 34:05.510
JARED BOWEN: These young
children are among the finalists
for acceptance into Project

34:05.510 --> 34:10.849
STEP. If chosen, they will be
plunged into an intensive music
immersion program.

34:10.849 --> 34:15.687
From now until they graduate
high school, they will take
weekly classes, receive
one-on-one

34:15.687 --> 34:21.593
lessons and they're expected to
complete hours of at-home
practice. And that's all on top

34:21.593 --> 34:27.532
of their regular schoolwork. At
this last stage of selection,
the students are divided

34:27.532 --> 34:32.203
into small groups for a month of
violin lessons perfecting how
they hold their bow, position

34:32.203 --> 34:35.974
their feet and read music.

34:35.974 --> 34:41.613
Susan Jarvis has been teaching
the class for 13 years,
scrutinizing their mastery of
music.

34:41.613 --> 34:45.317
SUSAN JARVIS, Teacher, Project
STEP: It's a matter of finding
which child -- which children

34:45.317 --> 34:52.023
can adapt to it the fastest.
Every child can do it in their
own time, but some kids are

34:52.023 --> 34:58.163
maybe a little more innately
coordinated or have a really
strong interest in it.

34:58.163 --> 35:00.598
Hands up if you know
where A-string is.

35:00.598 --> 35:02.600
JARED BOWEN: They are so young.

35:02.600 --> 35:03.868
SUSAN JARVIS: These
guys are old.

35:03.868 --> 35:05.637
(LAUGHTER)

35:05.637 --> 35:10.442
SUSAN JARVIS: These are a joy to
teach every year, because
they're 5 and 6 years old. And

35:10.442 --> 35:14.980
that's a big difference from the
3- and 4-year-olds, which I -- I
normally teach.

35:14.980 --> 35:20.185
JARED BOWEN: Just as important
as the music is what happens at
home. Project STEP will

35:20.185 --> 35:24.723
select only students who have
full parental involvement. In
class, they are fully behind

35:24.723 --> 35:26.858
the students.

35:26.858 --> 35:31.229
SUSAN JARVIS: Let's get some
help from your parents. They're
going to be your beat partners.

35:31.229 --> 35:36.001
They're going to keep your eyes
on the music, and you're going
to keep your eyes on their

35:36.001 --> 35:40.171
fingers.

35:40.171 --> 35:49.114
The parents are the lifeline. We
work pretty hard to tell the
parents what to do, how to

35:49.114 --> 35:52.851
do it, and how many times to do
it, because in teaching a string
instrument, there's just

35:52.851 --> 35:55.887
not a lot of room for
error at the beginning.

35:55.887 --> 36:00.025
AJANI BOYD, Student, Project
STEP: Personally, music just
calms me down. Like, it makes me

36:00.025 --> 36:02.293
feel good inside.

36:02.293 --> 36:07.098
JARED BOWEN: At 11 years old,
Ajani Boyd has now played with
Project STEP longer than he

36:07.098 --> 36:12.504
hasn't. He's all about the bass
now, but he was 4 when he chose
the cello.

36:12.504 --> 36:15.673
AJANI BOYD: I picked the cello.
And, honestly, I kind of picked
the cello because I could

36:15.673 --> 36:17.742
sit down.

36:17.742 --> 36:22.147
JARED BOWEN: He can be forgiven
the easy choice, given the
program's demands, practice
daily

36:22.147 --> 36:26.351
and up to nine hours
every Saturday.

36:26.351 --> 36:33.291
MARY JAFFEE: It's pretty
intense. The new measure of
10,000 hours of preparation,
rehearsal,

36:33.291 --> 36:37.195
practice, whatever it is, they
put it in by the time they're in
high school. It's an -- it's

36:37.195 --> 36:39.697
just an awful lot.

36:39.697 --> 36:43.902
JARED BOWEN: But it served Njeri
Grevious well. She's now a
sophomore at Yale University

36:43.902 --> 36:46.271
studying mathematics.

36:46.271 --> 36:50.508
Do you think about what would
have been if you didn't have an
opportunity like this?

36:50.508 --> 36:57.182
NJERI GREVIOUS, Yale University:
Very difficult, almost
impossible. I actually don't
want to

36:57.182 --> 36:59.951
think about that. I definitely
think it's -- I have been so
blessed.

36:59.951 --> 37:04.022
JARED BOWEN: Grevious spent 12
years in Project STEP, including
a time, she says, when her

37:04.022 --> 37:06.724
family was left homeless.

37:06.724 --> 37:11.796
NJERI GREVIOUS: When we were
living out of the car, when
sometimes it was very, very

37:11.796 --> 37:17.702
cold waking up in the morning,
no heating in the house, and
trying to practice, we pull

37:17.702 --> 37:20.472
-- were able to put all that
aside, because, when we're
engaging with our instruments,

37:20.472 --> 37:23.374
its just us, ourselves, our
instruments, our music.

37:23.374 --> 37:27.912
And then when we're playing with
other people, it's all of that
times -- to the nth power.

37:27.912 --> 37:32.884
And we're able to find
peace and solace.

37:32.884 --> 37:38.423
JARED BOWEN: Working off a tight
budget with money it receives
from foundations and individual

37:38.423 --> 37:42.894
donors, Project STEP subsidizes
virtually all the students'
expenses, roughly $9,000

37:42.894 --> 37:46.498
to $11,000 annually.

37:46.498 --> 37:50.168
It gives them opportunity, while
their base in the basement of
Symphony Hall gives them

37:50.168 --> 37:52.070
access.

37:52.070 --> 37:56.407
MARY JAFFEE: One parent put it
that she didn't think she could
touch Symphony Hall. She used

37:56.407 --> 38:00.678
to walk by it and thought it
just wasn't for her. And now
she's learned to navigate the

38:00.678 --> 38:04.382
halls and say hello to
some of the musicians.

38:04.382 --> 38:10.054
JARED BOWEN: And even play with
them. There are not many people,
let alone 11-year-olds,

38:10.054 --> 38:15.193
who can claim to have performed
on stage with one of the most
famous musicians of our time.

38:15.193 --> 38:19.330
NJERI GREVIOUS: Here is Yo-Yo
Ma, and then a little bit next
to him is me.

38:19.330 --> 38:21.833
(LAUGHTER)

38:21.833 --> 38:29.674
NJERI GREVIOUS: That was an
incredible opportunity that I
got, and I will never forget
that moment.

38:29.674 --> 38:33.678
JARED BOWEN: The moments don't
get much bigger, though, than
when Project STEP was honored

38:33.678 --> 38:38.516
by the White House late last
year with a National Arts and
Humanities Youth Program Award,
presented

38:38.516 --> 38:41.686
by first lady Michelle Obama.

38:41.686 --> 38:45.657
AJANI BOYD: It's just crazy to
be able to say, "when I came
back from the White House."

38:45.657 --> 38:50.395
I mean, it's -- being -- going
to the White House was amazing.
It was such a fun experience.

38:50.395 --> 38:55.266
Met a lot of people. I got to
meet the first lady. So it was
just awesome in all.

38:55.266 --> 38:59.837
JARED BOWEN: All of this is a
testament to the music and the
instruction, that in an

38:59.837 --> 39:04.509
age of attention deficits, these
students will practice thousands
of hours. In moments

39:04.509 --> 39:09.147
of crisis, music is
their salvation.

39:09.147 --> 39:14.085
All of Project STEP's 60
students have graduated high
school, and half of them have
gone on

39:14.085 --> 39:19.057
to the country's most
prestigious Ivy League schools
or conservatories. And Jaffee
says

39:19.057 --> 39:22.794
more than half of them are now
professional musicians
themselves.

39:22.794 --> 39:25.563
Does the program change lives?

39:25.563 --> 39:29.000
MARY JAFFEE: It does change
lives. I believe it does change
lives. It's certainly changed

39:29.000 --> 39:30.368
my life.

39:30.368 --> 39:34.606
JARED BOWEN: And many others
through the power of music.

39:34.606 --> 39:41.746
This is Jared Bowen from WGBH
for the "PBS NewsHour" in
Boston.

39:41.746 --> 39:54.926
GWEN IFILL: We will be back with
a look at the American heroin
epidemic.

39:54.926 --> 39:59.130
But, first, take a moment to
hear from your local PBS
station. You can have the
opportunity

39:59.130 --> 40:08.206
to offer your support, which
helps keep programs like ours on
the air.

40:08.206 --> 40:12.443
(BREAK)

40:12.443 --> 40:18.850
Now the latest addition to
the "NewsHour" Bookshelf.

40:18.850 --> 40:24.989
According to the Centers for
Disease Control, heroin usage in
the U.S. has doubled among

40:24.989 --> 40:29.894
young adults in the last decade
and deaths have quadrupled.

40:29.894 --> 40:36.067
Former Los Angeles Times
reporter Sam Quinones looks at
what's driving that surge in his

40:36.067 --> 40:40.772
new book, "Dreamland: The True
Tale of America's Opiate
Epidemic."

40:40.772 --> 40:45.843
He recently talked with Jeffrey
Brown and painted a graphic
portrait of a national problem.

40:45.843 --> 40:52.750
SAM QUINONES, Author,
"Dreamland: The True Tale of
America's Opiate Epidemic": This
is

40:52.750 --> 40:58.122
the quietest epidemic, drug
epidemic or drug scourge, we
have ever had in this country,

40:58.122 --> 41:01.259
certainly in the
last 50, 60 years.

41:01.259 --> 41:04.796
No public violence is
associated, not like crack,
where the people were battling
for

41:04.796 --> 41:11.669
street corners and this kind of
thing. People are dying alone in
their bedrooms, in a McDonald's

41:11.669 --> 41:16.574
bathroom. And there's no
publicity. Families are
stigmatized, horribly mortified
that their

41:16.574 --> 41:21.179
kids are addicted and then that
their kids die of this stuff.

41:21.179 --> 41:26.351
JEFFREY BROWN: So, this came
from reporting on the drug trade
in Mexico and the U.S. What

41:26.351 --> 41:28.886
grabbed your attention?

41:28.886 --> 41:36.494
SAM QUINONES: Well, I discovered
in the course of my reporting
the story of one small town

41:36.494 --> 41:38.996
in Mexico on the Pacific Coast,
where everybody in that town had
migrated to the United States,

41:38.996 --> 41:41.766
had developed a system
for selling heroin.

41:41.766 --> 41:46.204
They were master heroin
retailers in the United States,
selling heroin like pizza, like
delivery

41:46.204 --> 41:51.309
model. And they had used this
system to, first of all, employ
hundreds of people in the town

41:51.309 --> 41:54.979
and spread across the country,
so they were in like half the
country.

41:54.979 --> 41:58.816
What I also came to understand,
though, was that they had this
enormous market for heroin.

41:58.816 --> 42:04.889
This one small town became one
of the major suppliers of heroin
to the United States.

42:04.889 --> 42:09.794
That market was due entirely to
a whole new supply of addicts
who got addicted to prescription

42:09.794 --> 42:11.629
painkillers.

42:11.629 --> 42:15.466
JEFFREY BROWN: So it's actually
a tale of two kinds of drugs,
right, two opiates.

42:15.466 --> 42:17.635
SAM QUINONES: Two opiates.

42:17.635 --> 42:21.205
JEFFREY BROWN: One is legal in
the U.S., prescription drugs for
pain.

42:21.205 --> 42:22.707
SAM QUINONES: Right.

42:22.707 --> 42:26.244
JEFFREY BROWN: And then there's
this heroin market on top of
that.

42:26.244 --> 42:28.279
Somehow, they're linked.

42:28.279 --> 42:32.617
SAM QUINONES: Yes. And what
connects them is that this is a
new kind of drug trafficking

42:32.617 --> 42:36.521
in a sense. It's all based
on branding and marketing.

42:36.521 --> 42:40.758
It's no longer based on the old
style of gunplay and shoot-outs
for street corners and all

42:40.758 --> 42:43.261
that kind of scuff.

42:43.261 --> 42:46.431
JEFFREY BROWN: It's not the
cartels that we have been
hearing, where all the violence

42:46.431 --> 42:48.433
is.

42:48.433 --> 42:53.004
SAM QUINONES: Exactly. These are
the anti-cartels, the
anti-"Scarface," you might say.
These

42:53.004 --> 42:58.910
guys are all about low profile.
They're all about branding their
drugs, making sure that

42:58.910 --> 43:04.782
you know, every time you buy a
little 10th-of-a-gram balloon of
heroin from them, that you know

43:04.782 --> 43:11.355
exactly what's in it, that you
can call if it's no good and
have it replaced.

43:11.355 --> 43:17.128
At the same time, though, the
companies that promoted the
pills have also used branding

43:17.128 --> 43:20.631
and marketing to convince
doctors all across America that
these pills can be used without

43:20.631 --> 43:21.699
risk, without risk of addiction,
virtually nonaddictive when used
to address...

43:21.699 --> 43:23.601
(CROSSTALK)

43:23.601 --> 43:27.138
JEFFREY BROWN: Well, that is
where the story starts in the
U.S., right, is the rise of

43:27.138 --> 43:28.940
these kinds of pills that many
people are familiar with,
whether you're an athlete or

43:28.940 --> 43:30.575
any -- all kinds
of people, right?

43:30.575 --> 43:32.977
SAM QUINONES: Sure. Right.

43:32.977 --> 43:36.981
JEFFREY BROWN: Pain, you get
prescribed these kinds of pills.
And you were told that they

43:36.981 --> 43:39.784
were nonaddictive, or
mostly not addictive.

43:39.784 --> 43:44.322
SAM QUINONES: You were told they
were nonaddictive, or you
weren't told anything. You were
just

43:44.322 --> 43:49.660
given a big whack of pills. I
had my appendix out, they gave
me 60 Vicodin to take home.

43:49.660 --> 43:52.530
The message in that bottle was,
doesn't matter how many of these
you take. It's not going

43:52.530 --> 43:55.066
to addict you.

43:55.066 --> 44:04.308
You're not -- they didn't tell
me anything about what was in
them. I think is kind of

44:04.308 --> 44:09.780
common practice all across the
country because of this pain
revolution that took place in

44:09.780 --> 44:14.452
the '80s and well into the '90s,
gaining a lot of momentum then.

44:14.452 --> 44:17.321
JEFFREY BROWN: Much of it to
benefit to people, right?

44:17.321 --> 44:21.025
SAM QUINONES: Of course. No,
these are legitimate pills, and
many people use them to great
benefit.

44:21.025 --> 44:26.664
And it has assuaged the pain of
many, many people, chronic pain,
as well as post-surgical

44:26.664 --> 44:29.133
pain.

44:29.133 --> 44:34.739
The problem is, there is not a
lot of attempt to just determine
who should be taking them,

44:34.739 --> 44:48.052
how many pills they should take
home with them. And there is not
a lot of time spent

44:48.052 --> 45:07.438
by doctors on dealing with maybe
a patient's history of
addiction, say, in the past,
what

45:07.438 --> 45:16.113
-- do you have any addiction,
history of alcoholism?

45:16.113 --> 45:20.484
JEFFREY BROWN: And what's been
the result? This is -- you
describe it, throughout Middle

45:20.484 --> 45:21.118
America especially.

45:21.118 --> 45:22.887
SAM QUINONES: Right.

45:22.887 --> 45:25.623
JEFFREY BROWN: An epidemic?
What do you see?

45:25.623 --> 45:28.893
SAM QUINONES: I see epidemic.

45:28.893 --> 45:34.966
I see a scourge that has
attacked communities that are
completely unprepared for this.
They

45:34.966 --> 45:41.439
have never seen anything like
it. It's families who never
really had this kind of
addiction

45:41.439 --> 45:45.943
to hard drugs ever in their
lives. It's hitting rural areas.
It's hitting suburban areas.

45:45.943 --> 45:52.116
Athletes -- it now seems to me,
frankly, that at times football
is almost a gateway to heroin

45:52.116 --> 45:56.487
addiction, because so many
football players are treated for
their chronic pain with these

45:56.487 --> 46:00.391
pills. They then get addicted
and eventually -- if it's not
treated, eventually, you have

46:00.391 --> 46:05.863
to transition to heroin
after using these pills.

46:05.863 --> 46:10.601
JEFFREY BROWN: So, what kind of
awareness is there now, either
in the medical community,

46:10.601 --> 46:15.573
in government? What
is or could be done?

46:15.573 --> 46:39.130
SAM QUINONES: I think what needs
to be happen is very much what
began happening with the AIDS
epidemic, and

46:39.130 --> 46:45.936
that is a recognition and
talking a lot about it, removing
that stigma.

46:45.936 --> 46:59.183
Once you remove it, then people
who get -- who are new to it can
figure out what their kids

46:59.183 --> 47:16.434
need. But that's what has not
happened. That's why I think it
has spread.

47:16.434 --> 47:43.594
JEFFREY BROWN: All
right, the book

47:43.594 --> 47:48.899
is "Dreamland."

47:48.899 --> 48:05.549
Sam Quinones, thank you so much.

48:05.549 --> 48:20.965
SAM QUINONES: My
pleasure. Thank you.

